[src:dutch-fehring/1932-all-big-ten-conference-football-team] The **1932 All-Big Ten Conference football team** consists of American football players selected to the All-Big Ten Conference teams chosen by various selectors for the 1932 Big Ten Conference football season.
[src:dutch-fehring/1933-all-big-ten-conference-football-team] The **1933 All-Big Ten Conference football team** consists of American football players selected to the All-Big Ten Conference teams chosen by various selectors for the 1933 Big Ten Conference football season.
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-chicago-white-sox-season] The **1934 Chicago White Sox season** was the team's 34th season in the major leagues and its 35th season overall.
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-chicago-white-sox-season] They finished with a record of 53–99, good enough for eighth and last place in the American League (47 games behind the first place Detroit Tigers).
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-major-league-baseball-season] The **1934 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1934.
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 30, with the St.
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals and Detroit Tigers as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 31st World Series on October 3 and ended with Game 7 on October 9.
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-major-league-baseball-season] The Cardinals then defeated the Tigers, four games to three, capturing their third championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1931.
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Giants from the 1933 season.
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-major-league-baseball-season] The second All-Star Game was held on July 10 at the Polo Grounds in New York, New York, home of the New York Giants.
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-major-league-baseball-season] The 1934 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day, April 17, featured all sixteen teams, the first since the 1931 season.
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 30, which also saw all sixteen teams play, continued the trend which began with the 1930 season.
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-major-league-baseball-season] This was the second time that both Opening Day and the final day of the season saw all sixteen teams play, the previous being in 1931.
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 3 and October 9.
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-major-league-baseball-season] 8 tie games (5 in AL, 3 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 3 and ended on October 9 with the St.
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals defeating the Detroit Tigers in the 1934 World Series in seven games.
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-major-league-baseball-season] After moving into Cleveland Stadium mid-way through the 1932 season, the Cleveland Indians move back into League Park due to plummeting attendance caused by the Great Depression.
[src:dutch-fehring/1934-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds' Redland Field is renamed to Crosley Field following the February 1934 purchase of the Reds by local businessman Powel Crosley Jr.
[src:dutch-fehring/1936-ncaa-baseball-season] The **1936 NCAA baseball season,** play of college baseball in the United States organized by the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) began in the spring of 1936.
[src:dutch-fehring/1936-ncaa-baseball-season] Play largely consisted of regional matchups, some organized by conferences, and ended in June.
[src:dutch-fehring/1936-ncaa-baseball-season] No national championship event was held until 1947.
[src:dutch-fehring/1936-ncaa-baseball-season] This is a partial list of conference champions from the 1936 season.
[src:dutch-fehring/1937-ncaa-baseball-season] The **1937 NCAA baseball season,** play of college baseball in the United States organized by the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) began in the spring of 1937.
[src:dutch-fehring/1937-ncaa-baseball-season] This is a partial list of conference champions from the 1937 season.
[src:dutch-fehring/1938-ncaa-baseball-season] The **1938 NCAA baseball season,** play of college baseball in the United States organized by the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) began in the spring of 1938.
[src:dutch-fehring/1938-ncaa-baseball-season] This is a partial list of conference champions from the 1938 season.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] A longtime college baseball coach, he served as the head baseball coach at Purdue University from 1936 to 1942 and at Stanford University from 1956 to 1967, compiling a career record of 374–248–9.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] He was a cup of coffee player with the Chicago White Sox of Major League Baseball, appearing in a single game during the 1934 season.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] Born in Columbus, Indiana, Fehring attended Purdue University, where he starred in football, basketball, and baseball, one of only two Purdue athletes to letter nine times.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] Fehring helped the Boilermakers win two Big Ten Conference titles in football and a retroactive Helms national championship in basketball in 1932, and was the traveling roommate of John Wooden.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] Fehring was inducted into the inaugural class of the Purdue University Athletic Hall of Fame in 1994.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] After graduating from Purdue, Fehring chose to play his favorite sport, baseball, where he excelled as a catcher.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] He was signed by the Chicago White Sox and made a single major league appearance, in a road game against the New York Yankees at Yankee Stadium on June 25, 1934.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] Fehring entered the game in the bottom of the seventh inning to catch, with the Yankees leading 10–2.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] During that inning, Lou Gehrig attempted an inside-the-park home run on a ball hit to center field; the ball was relayed to Fehring, who tagged Gehrig out at the plate.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] Gehrig was credited with a triple on the play; he had already hit a home run, single, and double in the game, thus it became the first time that Gehrig hit for the cycle in his career.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] Fehring had one at bat during the game, striking out in the ninth inning.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] After his baseball career ended, Fehring returned to Purdue and became their head baseball coach and assistant football coach from 1936 to 1942.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] After serving in World War II, Fehring was an assistant football coach for two years at Oklahoma and for one year at UCLA, where he recommended his college friend John Wooden for the head basketball coaching vacancy.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] In 1949, Fehring was hired as an assistant baseball and football coach at Stanford.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] He took over as head baseball coach in 1956, and coached for 11 years, culminating in a College World Series semifinals appearance in 1967.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] Along with his football coaching role in the 1952 Rose Bowl, Fehring has the unique distinction as a coach in both a College World Series and a Rose Bowl.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] Fehring was an assistant coach on the United States national baseball team that participated in the 1964 Olympic Games in Tokyo, under manager and USC coach Rod Dedeaux.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] On the 1964 Olympic team was catcher Jim Hibbs, who played under Fehring at Stanford.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] Fehring was named president of the United States Baseball Federation (USBF) on April 6, 1966, replacing Eppie Barnes.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] As president, Fehring saw the United States national team return to international stage; its appearance at the 1969 Amateur World Series in the Dominican Republic was the first time the U.S. participated in the tournament since 1942.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] Fehring was highly critical of the International Baseball Federation (FIBA) and its president, Juan Isa.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] He, like many others, believed that the Caribbean baseball federations had too much control over FIBA's proceedings.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] After the 1973 FIBA Congress ended in confusion and chaos, Italy and Nicaragua withdrew from FIBA to organize their own international federation; the USBF soon followed, along with 24 other national federations.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] Fehring was elected president of the new organization, titled FEMBA (or alternatively, WABAF) on September 8, 1973.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] As head of FEMBA, a major priority for Fehring was the inclusion of baseball at the Summer Olympics.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] This had been a factor in the FEMBA split, as critics of FIBA felt that the federation was too chaotic to pursue Olympic status.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] Fehring, with the backing of MLB Commissioner Bowie Kuhn, met with International Olympic Committee head Lord Killanin, but was told that would not occur as long as baseball was represented by two different organizations.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] Fehring was succeeded as FEMBA president by Carlos García Solórzano in 1975.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] After the FEMBA-FIBA split was resolved in 1976, he joined the unified committee of AINBA, later the IBAF (the predecessor to the modern World Baseball Softball Confederation).
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] Under IBAF president Robert Smith, Fehring recruited Rod Dedeaux to help the federation gain Olympic status; thanks to Dedeaux and Los Angeles Dodgers owner Peter O'Malley, baseball returned to the Olympics at the 1984 Los Angeles Games.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] Fehring retired as head baseball coach in 1967, but remained at Stanford as director of intramurals and club sports until 1977.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] He also stepped down as president of the U.S.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] Fehring died in Palo Alto, California, in 2006 at the age of 93.
[src:dutch-fehring/dutch-fehring] Fehring is an inductee of the American Baseball Coaches Association Hall of Fame, the Indiana Baseball Hall of Fame, the Indiana Basketball Hall of Fame, the Purdue University Athletic Hall of Fame, and the Stanford Athletic Hall of Fame.
